The change involves replacing a multi-statement sequence (an assignment and two conditional `if` blocks) with a single, complex ternary expression. The TriggerPattern DSL is designed for expression-level or single-statement replacements, not for arbitrarily transforming and collapsing multiple statements and control flow into a single, complex expression. This requires capabilities beyond simple pattern matching and replacement. For example, replacing:

`String release = $project.getOption(JavaCore.COMPILER_RELEASE, true);
if (release == null) {
    release = $project.getOption(JavaCore.COMPILER_CODEGEN_TARGET_PLATFORM, true);
}
if (release == null) {
    release = JavaCore.latestSupportedJavaVersion();
}`

with:

`String release = JavaCore.ENABLED.equals($project.getOption(JavaCore.COMPILER_RELEASE, true))
        ? $project.getOption(JavaCore.COMPILER_COMPLIANCE, true) : null;`

is a non-trivial structural rewrite.
